Author: Tom Brand | StarkWare#1971
Content:
That's a great question. I think in general there are less tools then one would assume. This is because the interface and the flow of StarkNet remains mostly the same. Nevertheless, we are working very closely with the tools to try and make this migration as soon as possible. To elaborate a bit - 
1. SDKs ( StarkNet.py, StarkNet.js, etc..) - they have the least amount of work as the interface of StarkNet does not change.
2. testing frameworks (protostar, hardhat) - many changes, some of them are already working on the migration (Protostar for example)
3. devnet - same as SDKs, not a lot of changes. They do need to support changes resulted by StarkNet v0.11.0, but I think this is not that big.

Author: 0xdarlington
pilou_sekai
Content:
1. I'd say the double parentheses is necessary because `(owner, spender)` is a tuple and not two separate values (please someone correct me if I am wrong).

2. `0xffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffff_u128` is the maximum value a `uint128` can take. A `uint256` is the combination a  `low uint128` and `high uint128`. Hence this checks if the current allowance is the maximum a `uint256` can take, what is also called infinite allowance in case of ERC20 standard. It's already the case in OZ ERC 20 contract both in Solidity in Cairo (https://github.com/OpenZeppelin/openzeppelin-contracts/blob/master/contracts/token/ERC20/ERC20.sol#L324 / https://github.com/OpenZeppelin/cairo-contracts/blob/main/src/openzeppelin/token/erc20/library.cairo#L284). Basically, in the case of an infinite allowance, the allowance amount is not spent. More explanation here : https://www.aktionariat.com/documentation/infinite-erc-20-allowances.

Author: punk5736
Content: @Fox Reymann Yes, once the regenesis is over transactions which invoke Cairo 0.X contracts will fail. I believe this is because on-chain Cairo 1.0 contracts are deployed as Sierra IR, whereas Cairo 0.X contracts are deployed as CASM. On top of that, Starknet OS can't prove Cairo 0.X contract execution which fails, leaving the system open to DOS.

Author: punk5736
Content:
It's unclear to me how to take a trait definition and implement it on my contract. I define my contract as a `mod` but, assuming the language constructs mimic Rust, I can't implement a trait on a module. Maybe the `#[contract]` proc macro transforms the module into a struct and I could then implement the trait on that struct. A tool analogous to `cargo-expand` might help me here.

Is there any public discussion on how the Cairo compiler is being shaped to support the Starknet and non-Starknet use cases?

Author: punk5736
Content:
Since `cairo-compile` and `starknet-compile` are already separate, it seems like the Starknet compiler should be able to introduce domain specific concepts into the grammar, maybe even something similar to the  `contract` and `library` reserved words in Solidity. The current approach feels, to me after a couple of days of learning, like it's taking on too many Rust semantics and as a result is not tailored enough for the Starknet domain. 

I'm still working to catch up on the short to medium term roadmap and also prior design considerations, however I'm not finding these discussions on the Github. Is there a thread somewhere I could use to get up to date?

Content:
Maybe a ctor. Events (not sure if they should actually come from the trait, but that's also unclear how to do in a trait).

Author: punk5736
Content:
I was wondering something similar. It would make sense to me that you don't `impl` explicitly in Cairo 1.0 like you do in Rust, instead you just implement the functions the trait requires and if you implement a trait completely then that contract has implicitly implemented a trait. If you think about, this makes sense because the compiler has no knowledge of the contract your contract will call at runtime and it also has no knowledge of the interface other contracts will be using to call your contract at runtime. Meaning, there would be limited utility in having the compiler ensure your contract conforms to a trait definition.

The trait is useful for the contract calling a contract which implements the expected trait. The trait definition helps the calling contract encode the function call, including the arguments, for the CALL syscall. This would be similar to Solidity. If the contract being called doesn't have a function with the required function selector which is derived from the trait definition, then the call will fail.

Author: punk5736
Content: ... I might be wrong here, but just reasoning through it

Author: spapini#3824
Content:
I don't like this suggestion. The compiler should have knowledge about what you are trying to implement and should enforce type safety. I very very much dislike this umsafety we have in solidity and cairo0.
It also doesn't conform with the idea of "typed starknet" (Adding linear type semantic to intercontract calls, like MOVE based languages, which has a lot of benefits)

This also has a problem of colliding functions. If i want to be both ERC20 and ERC721, or even implement ERC20 twice.

I strongly believe that abi should be declared as traits. When you implement them you "use" them as a crate in your code, and just do an impl. You can have multiple impls for your code.
When calling other contracts, you do it via a Dispatcher impl of the abi trait

```how the code will be generated for each macro?```

Author: eni7912
Content:
no, it means that the compiler was modified in Dojo to support code generation from these macros.

The use case is that it allows you to write less code to do more because the compiler will generate the required code for you üòÑ  in that case, each component and system has the same template code, so we can just generate it instead of writing it by hand

Content: Fo example, taking a snapshot of an array, and then appending to the array, the snapshot won't reflect the new change.

Content: It's meant to be used like rust's &, for example, for methods that don't modify the instance

Author: punk5736
Content:
I see. Yeah, just thinking through how to implement the `read` function ...

If the `base` address had the length and the elements of the array were stored sequentially in memory, then you could devise some algorithms to read the entire array. Would need to think of the patterns for when elements are non-felts or collection types, including packing types smaller than felts like `u8`.

For the write function it seems like you would only ever need to write to an index, not write the whole array. Which makes me think that maybe the storage for an array might benefit from being built through composition. The problem being that the `Array::<T>` needs to implement `StorageAccess` the way the storage mechanics are set up right now.

Hmm. Is there a fundamental reason why arrays are not supported by Starknet storage?

Author: gaetbout
Content:
Couldn't we do the same as in the Serde file ?
When effectively storing in memory (so when write is called), you could first write the size of the array, then each element.
Then to read you should read a felt then read X time to reconstitute the array it is was stored?

Author: eni7912
Content: that would probably work, yes

Author: gaetbout
Content: But it would consume 1 more storage slot

Author: eni7912
Content:
> Is there a fundamental reason why arrays are not supported by Starknet storage? 
No idea, I would think that it's only a matter of specifying how to read/write arrays to storage rather than a limitation of Starknet itself. In the end, you end up only writing felts anyway...

Author: eni7912
Content:
I was also thinking about variable packing like the solidity compiler does
We can implement our own serde::StorageAccess implementation for structs. So if we have a struct composed of various integer types, we can explicitly define how we can pack them together in the `StorageAccess::read` and unpack them in the `StorageAccess::write` function and benchmark how effective this gas saving is

Author: eni7912
Content: If we still go by the motto `computation is cheap, storage is expensive` and given that storage updates represent the major part of tx costs, it could be interesting

Author: eni7912
Content:
just thinking out loud but if we need to store on-chain parameters that are related to each other (meaning that when one changes, the other change as well), like for example some kind of royalty mechanism with the following parameters

```rust
struct Packed{
  on : bool
  fee_amt : u8
  recipient : ContractAddress
}
```

we can probably pack them in a single storage slot, thus reducing the update cost by 2048 gas which is like $0.1 right now. The Cairo 1 compiler and bitwise operation make it a lot easier now than it was with Cairo0 ...

Author: eni7912
Content:
1. impossible for now, your error message must fit in 31 bytes.
2. This will be reworked soon in Starklings with the latest additions to the core library. But basically the external `print` function takes an array of felts and displays them.

3. `extern` means that it's not a "pure" cairo function, but high-level function that translates to a Sierra libfunc for which we can generate the correspondig CASM code
- array_append is implemented in the cairo compiler, `corelib/src/array.cairo`

4. `mut` variables are just syntaxic sugar. `ref` can only be applied to mutable variables, the eq in rust is `&mut ref`

5. This is for the "garbage collection" feature of Cairo1/Sierra that ensures that each variable is either consumed or dropped. I believe that this statement generates the code for the Drop behavior for this type.

Author: eni7912
Content: https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo/blob/main/crates/cairo-lang-sierra/src/extensions/modules/drop.rs see here for drop

Author: wind.rider
Content:
ser,and pls check:it is not supported by design - as it is not safe operations - for cheatcodes usages - additional libfuncs are added by extenders to enable testing frameworks for directly accessing the vm.
if you require hints for optimization purposes - please share it with us - and a libfunc implementating this optimization may be added to support this.

Author: wind.rider
Content:
Sorry,ser,there‚Äòre also replies from the team, in addition to my reply to your second question, which you can refer to:
1„ÄÅIf you want to print more than one value - just split it into two prints.
3„ÄÅ`extern fn ... ` are functions that are implemented in the sierra level - these are provided as the final "linkage level" of the compiler.
4„ÄÅit is also similar to rust - where you cannot modify a non-`mut` var. we hope to expand resources on the subject soon.
5„ÄÅthe trait system is indeed `of `based instead of `for` based - a trait is not provided `for` a type - instead an `impl` is an implementation of a `trait` - when calling a `trait` method - we would find some` impl` matching it. `Copy` and `Drop` are special - they do not have an implementation - they just mark the type as a type that can be copied (having an additional ref to the same point in memory) or dropped (no longer referring to a value in memory, without any special action such as `dict_squash`)
thank youü§ù

Author: eni7912
Content:
it's not what you should be thinking about when using snapshots

The reasoning should be, imo :
- Do I need to reuse this value later in the calling function context ? -> if not, pass by value
- Do I need to reuse this value later in the calling function context AND modify it in the called function ? -> pass by ref
- Do I need to reuse this value later in the calling function context without it being modified in the called function ? -> pass by snapshot

most likely in your example, you don't want to modify the struct and you might want to reuse it afterward, so in that case, you'd use a snapshot. It would be less efficient to use `ref` as you'd need to push more values to memory before returning from the function context

Content: what's the difference btw `contract_address_to_felt` and `ContractAddressIntoFelt`?

Author: milan3774
Content:
the latter is the name for the implementation of the `Into` trait for `<ContractAddress, felt>` types - the trait itself declares one function, `into`, which allows us to call `let f: felt = my_contract_address.into()`

the former is the actual function that is being called to perform the conversion, in the body of the `into`; it's a internal library function, implemented in Rust

Content: look at the test function `fn check_icecream`. There are three time groups you need to account for: before 10pm (`22_usize`), 10pm to before 12am, and then 12am and later. Does that help?

Author: kale2747
Content: I‚Äòm still confused. Isn't the input range for 12am and later(till 10pm) is [0, 22]? And 10pm to before 12am is [22,24]? So two group is enough?

Author: whatthedev
Content: The third group is for any value 24 or higher, so [24, infinity), you need an Option::None(()). Also the first two ranges should be open at the high limit, like [0, 22) because at 10pm the value is 0, and [22, 24) because at 12am is out of bounds (we know because the last part of the test is `assert(maybe_icecream(25_usize).is_none(), 'err_5');`).

Author: danml
Content:
Hi everyone. I'm a dev who started a blockchain project early last year on Solana, primarily due to the incredibly quick and low transaction costs (my concept requires frequent, very low cost transactions to be feasible).

I scrapped the project last year, but have recently considered picking it back up. I want to research pros/cons of rebuilding in starknet. My understanding is that Starknet claims to offer cheap/fast transactions, but I'm looking for hard numbers to understand just how cheap/expensive compute is in comparison to Solana. 

I'd also like to understand other elements of comparison: are there features offered by one and not possible on the other?  Is generating a VRF easily accessible on Starknet (it's fairly difficult on Solana)? What about contract upgradeability and ability to have control over the project as it's launched?

---
Asking all the above mainly to ask the following question: Where's the best place to chat with devs that can answer these types of questions? I'd love resources both within and outside this discord!

Content:
There are a few patterns of passing stuff. If you want it mutable, u don't have a lot of choice except ref. If you want a snapshot, you could either pass @v or Box<@v> - which is a smart pointer.

Expected: "@core::felt252", found: "core::felt252"`. Ideas how to fix? This is my assert: `assert(got_signers.at(0_u32) == 25_felt252, 'hmm');`

Author: laurip
Content: My guess: bitwise operators on felts are very costly and the concept of negative numbers is a bit vague.

Author: eni7912
Content: `assert(*got_signers.at(0_u32) == 25_felt252, 'hmm');`

Author: eni7912
Content: because array.at takes a snapshot as parameter and thus returns the snapshot of a value that you must desnap

Author: laurip
Content: Awesome, works, thanks

Author: laurip
Content: the error message was just rather..weird

Author: eni7912
Content: well the error message just said that you tried to compare a type `@felt` with a `felt`

Author: laurip
Content: what's the difference?

Author: laurip
Content: was trying to google for snapshots, but didn't find anything reasonable. Unless this is "Rust snapshot testing. In which case I need to figure out what that is üôÇ

Author: eni7912
Content: https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo/blob/main/docs/reference/src/cairo/modules/ROOT/pages/linear-types.adoc#snapshot

Author: eni7912
Content: It's not very clear yet but we're working on it for the Cairo book. Basically it's an immutable view of a type at a certain time that can safely be copied and dropped

Author: laurip
Content: like a copy?

Author: eni7912
Content: hmm not really, what you really want to achieve with snapshots is immutability

Author: eni7912
Content: so when you take a snapshot of an array you're sure that it won't ever mutate. You can have multiple instances of array snapshots and you're sure that none of them is going to accidently mutate your array

Author: eni7912
Content: it's like an immutable reference

Author: eni7912
Content: afaik it's a higher level concept that doesn't translate into CASM code, it's just used for type safety

Author: laurip
Content: cool, thanks

Content: What happens when you desnap a snapshot? Does it make a "deep copy" of the value and write it in a new memory cell?

Author: gmyanfeng

Author: spapini#3824
Content:
No. Desnapping has no cost, it's just a type safety thing. It's the same cost as moving by value.
A clone is a deep copy.

However, moving by value has a cost like in other languages. Essentially, pushing values. In case of an array, these are 2 vakues. Start and end pointers.

Author: laurip
Content: hmm, isn't classhash just a generic representation of a contract, it's not "aware" of any deployed instance (address). how could I convert from hash to address?

Author: gaetbout
Content:
Purely code wise the how is do-able that way:
`contract_address_try_from_felt252(my_class_hash_value.into()).unwrap()`
Otherwise I'm not sure I understand what you mean

Author: laurip
Content: well, as I've understood classhash, is that it's kind of a hash for the contract source code. and upon deployment we say "use this classhash with these parameters" and some underlying piece has source codes for each classhash

Author: augustbleeds
phil26
Content:
For information, the just released starknet.js v5.6.1 is now able to handle some of the cairo 1 types :
- bool, u8, u16, u32, usize, u64, u128, u256, ContractAddress are compatible.
- Tuple, struct and array (made of predefined types) are compatible.
- Complex objects, some mix of types are not yet compatible. In this case, follow the rules defined in the tuto : https://github.com/PhilippeR26/starknet.js-workshop-typescript/blob/main/Cairo1.md

Author: degendeveloper.eth
Content: If i want to extend/add additional logic around an erc20 contract, i can put the basic code from the example (https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo/blob/main/crates/cairo-lang-starknet/test_data/erc20.cairo) into an erc20.cairo file, then my additional logic in a abc.cairo file, then in my lib.cairo i just say mod erc20; mod abc; ?

Author: augustbleeds
Content: You'll also need to redefine all external/view functions in your abc.cairo contract. Cairo doesn't have inheritance, so if abc.cairo imports erc20.cairo it doesn't inherit functionality. So you'd have to redefine balance_of, transfer, transfer_from, name, decimals, etc.

Author: degendeveloper.eth
Content: would the easier route be to just put all the logic of the erc20 in my extended contract ?

Author: augustbleeds
Content: That'd work, but it wouldn't be as clean in my opinion. It's not too much work to create a seperate contract and use the erc20 in it.

Author: milan3774
Content: what happens if I call a contract which but the function I'm calling does not exist / is not public / argument count does not match... ?

Author: augustbleeds
Content: Arrays are not Copyable. Your function either has to accept a snapshot operator `@` or take in a mutable reference `ref x`

Author: augustbleeds
Content: If the function selector does not exist you'll get an entrypoint does not exist panic. Probably similar for is not public situation but you'll have to test it out to be confident. I'm not sure about argument count though. In solidity it's not guarenteed to revert I think -- calldata might be cut off. Not sure about what happens in starknet

Author: gaetbout
Content: if not exist SELECTOR_NOT_FOUND, if not public idk, Argument count doesn't match it'll try and parse and then tell TOO LONG or TOO SHORT

Author: zkcarter
Content: Hello everyone, I am currently migrating my project from cairo0 to cairo1. In cairo0, I have a struct that contains a felt252 array, in which the element size is 248 bits and requires division to perform calculations on the array elements. I noticed that felt252 does not provide division support in cairo1. This means that I need to use u128 or u256 to organize data when migrating to cairo1. Since felt252 is the basic unit, this may mean that a lot of storage space needs to be filled with 0s to organize the data. I want to know if this will result in wasted data space and an increase in gas fees?

Author: gaetbout
Content: Think so üòÑ

Author: milan3774
Content: if you opt in for u256 and the element values are actually >= 2*128, then yes, because you will use 2 storage slots to save them

Content: Thank you for your response. I would like to confirm that the size of a storage slot is 2^252, right?

Author: milan3774
Content: you mean the max value? that's max(felt252) right now, so something between 2^251 and 2^252

Author: drcapyvara
Content:
For anyone having language server issues:

1. make sure old cairo is uninstalled completely if you ever had it
2. reinstall cairo from scratch and get the latest version of scarb, follow the guide at https://cairo-book.github.io/ch01-01-installation.html for scarb and cairo
3. start with a completely clean project using `scarb new hello`, if it is still failing then you have an installation problem somewhere
4. if it works after following these steps but fails intermittently, then it is broken. I am currently experiencing language server crashes when using pattern matching statements.

Ive tested this on both debian and macos

Author: jojo_6251
Content: If the entire DEX were to use u128, but considering that Starknet, ETH, and other tokens appear to use u256, would it be more efficient in terms of gas savings to stick with u128, or would it consume more gas if u256 needs to be converted to u128?

Author: drcapyvara
Content: thats a good question, u256 has double the bit size as u128, meaning twice as much data can be stored. If gas is charged based on the amount of data stored, then u256 will cost more, although they give higher precision if you need it, so there is a tradeoff. the felt252 type does not currently have the same safety checks as the integer types, although it may be a cheaper way to store data in the future. it is worth paying attention to as the language evolves.

Author: technovision99
Content: Had a question about how `felt252` was implemented, is every computation done modulo the field prime, or does `felt252` just take up 252 bits of space? I was a bit confused then why this check was necessary in the `ecdsa` library: https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo/blob/60a42a39733c72840f7a1dd07e3993fab5f2ea6b/corelib/src/ecdsa.cairo#L36-L41

Author: technovision99
Content: I was also confused by the comment saying that `r,s < ec::StarkCurve::ORDER`, if `r,s` are felts shouldn't this be impossible as well?

Author: 0xspleen
Content:
Its a check among many validations that are required when implementing signature verification on a curve
also the ecdsa here refers to the starkcurve specifically. since ecdsa can be defined over different curves
if you want the evm one you have to build one using corelib/src/starknet/secp256k1.cairo

Author: 0xspleen
Content: you can find the curve params here https://docs.starkware.co/starkex/crypto/stark-curve.html

Author: technovision99
Content: I understand the check but my point is that the felt types are always less than the curve order right? So isn't this not needed? Or can felt252 be greater than the curve order?

Author: 0xspleen
Content: curve order is different from curve prime

Author: 0xspleen
Content: all felt operations are mod the prime

Author: Bwee#1503
Content:
I'm guessing that all parameters in an abi must be serializable/deserializable. Which makes sense since we have to cast calldata into types. But snapshots `@` are not serializable (Array spans have snapshots).

Also, I doubt it makes sense to have a snapshot in an interface since snapshots are reference to memory. But memory doesn't persist between transactions. Why not just use `Array<felt252>`?

Author: milan3774
Content:
IMO easiest (and what I've done elsewhere) is to compute the base addr from name using the old cairo-lang python function
```python
from starkware.starknet.public.abi import get_storage_var_address
var_addr = get_storage_var_address('foo')
```

and then in cairo hash it with the params together, sth like
```
let tmp = hash::LegacyHash::hash(var_addr, param1);
let tmp = hash::LegacyHash::hash(tmp, param2);
let base_addr = starknet::storage_base_address_from_felt252(tmp);
```

Author: jojo_6251
Content:
dir: `cairo/crates/cairo-lang-starknet/src/allowed_libfuncs_lists/`
left: `testnet_v0.1.0.json`
right:`experimental_v0.1.0.json`

Author: jojo_6251
Content: My guess is that because these methods were not included in testnet_v0.1.0.json, adding "--allowed-libfuncs-list-name experimental_v0.1.0" allows them to be compiled locally into Sierra and/or Casm.

Author: jojo_6251
Content: However, when Starknet (sequencer?) compiles Sierra into Casm during declaration, it does not include "-allowed-libfuncs-list-name experimental_v0.1.0", so they cannot be compiled into Casm and thus cannot be deployed on the testnet.

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: Exactly. This is not about compiler version but about allowed libfuncs. Since libfuncs are sensitive, once a new one is introduced, it starts in the experimental list and will only go to testnet after some auditing.

Author: jojo_6251
Content: Thank you for your response.:happy:  So, should we now use alternative methods to replace these libfuncs until they are allowed to run on the corresponding network?

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: If you're working locally / with devnet then you can use the experimental list (it's a compilation flag). It just won't be available on the real Starknets until they mature.

Content: I will  dive into devnet and Starknet.js. Thank you!

Author: laurip
Content:
I'm having troubles getting the `should_panic` decorator for unit tests to work with a message.
This is my decorator: `#[should_panic(expected: ('invalid signer',))]` and my test fails with `panicked with [2138404743268917596158051467814258 ('invalid signer'), 23583600924385842957889778338389964899652 ('ENTRYPOINT_FAILED'), ].`. For some reason the error message isn't caught. My guess is that it's related to the ENTRYPOINT_FAILED thing, but no idea what that is and where it comes from. Ideas?

Author: laurip
Content: ahaa, just figured this out, by trial-and-error. one can add more error messages to the decorator. So this works: `#[should_panic(expected: ('invalid signer','ENTRYPOINT_FAILED'))]`

Author: laurip
Content: have to remember to add this second message to all panic tests. a bit silly.

The type for StorageAddress is only valid in the range [0, 2**251) and the type StorageBaseAddress is only valid in the range [0, 2**251 - 256) - for successive writes we use StorageBaseAddress + u8 which results in StorageAddress.

Author: martriay
Content:
there's an initial version in our cairo-1 WIP branch, but it's not fully ready to use since we're still adapting it to work with dual interfaces as explained in our interface migration plan

it already supports calls for both interfaces, but not for outgoing calls such as `safeTransferFrom`'s `supportsInterface`, `onERC721Received`

https://github.com/OpenZeppelin/cairo-contracts/tree/cairo-1

Author: martriay
Content: also there's ongoing work on account contracts' erc165 (SNIP-5 now) which leaves open the door to what interface ID should be used, critical for `safeTransferFrom`'s checks

Content: see: https://github.com/ericnordelo/SNIPs/blob/feat/standard-interface-detection/SNIPS/snip-5.md

Content:
The code below has 3 different ways to find `b`. Each version runs fine using `cairo-run . --available-gas 10000000`. 

But when I use `scarb build` only  `let b = 0 - a` works. The other two versions fail with `error: Illegal bigint value during serialization.`

```
#[contract]
mod Negative {
    #[view]
    fn main() -> felt252 {
        let a = 1;

        // Keep just 1 of these (comment out the other 2):
        let b = -a; // error: Illegal bigint value during serialization.
        let b = -1 * a; // error: Illegal bigint value during serialization.
        let b = 0 - a; // no error

        b
    }
}
```

Also, if I comment out `#[view]`, then `scarb build` works fine for all 3 versions.

Using:
scarb 0.3.0 (4f90ec570 2023-06-01)
cairo: 1.1.0 (0e81e72d0)

Anyone know why `let b = -a` and `let b = -1 * a` cause the error when it's in a `#view` function?

Author: akirillo
Content:
Can someone explain to me / show me in the compiler codebase exactly what happens when gas runs out in a program? It seems like it reads the latest item off the stack as an error message?

More to the point, I'm trying to write some code that will do as much of a repetitive action as it can before the transaction gas limit is hit. My plan is to use `withdraw_gas` to check if the next iteration can be done, but if `withdraw_gas` returns `None`, does the program *need* to panic? Or can I just simply not do another iteration

Author: eni7912
Content: I think if withdraw_gas returns None, it means that you don't have enough gas remaning to safely execute the current iteration + exit the execution context. I guess that it needs to panic, but I'm not 100% sure

Author: akirillo
eni7912
Content: hmm, if withdraw_gas_all removes the gas cost of the most expensive path of the function, then it could be possible that it works well because `return i` is less expensive than another function call ü§î

Author: eni7912
Content: just trying to link this to this talk. Not sure if it makes sense to reason this way https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wYxUedcdVZ4

Author: akirillo
Content: mm yeah that makes sense, i recall that being what `withdraw_gas_all` does... but still, maybe I got lucky? I'll try with a lot of available gas, because my worry is that if we're like 1000000 stack frames deep then unwinding them *will* be more expensive than a return? like if i actually allocate variables in each recursion

Author: akirillo
Content: thank you for the link, I'll check that out

Author: eni7912
Content:
> like if i actually allocate variables in each recursion 
I think that's also taking into consideration when calling `withdraw_gas_all` . You add the execution cost + the unwinding cost of all introduced variables

Author: akirillo
Content: ah, if it factors in unwinding cost, then this feels like it should work :))

Content:

Since upcast and downcast operations seem not to be supported by Starknet at the moment, is there any workaround? For example, i have the following code where i try to add an u8 to an u128. Compiled to Sierra using Scarb this gives me an upcast operation.

};

When trying to deploy i get the following error:

Adding the flag as suggested by the error would not really help me since those experimental libfuncs will not be supported by Mainnet anyway, correct?

Author: gaetbout
Content:
If I understood correctly, Span is just a read access to memory with a starting pointer that you can increment (pop_front) or and ending pointer that you can decrement (pop_back)
 I'm prob responding beside the question but hope it help, somehow ^^'

Author: wind.rider
Content:
currently it holds 2 pointers - so that the second pointer is the next location to write.
Do note that this shouldn't actually affect the Cairo1 code - as this is an underlying implementation of Sierra-to-CASM, and Cairo1 is compiled to Sierra.about fp and ap - this is again just hidden - the compiler decide where to put variables `temp` or `local` according to what is necessary for the variable.

Author: glihm
Content:
On starknet accounts are smart contract. A wallet is just a piece of software that manage your private key and generate signature for transactions.

Yes, you need your account to have some ETH already sent to its address to deploy it.

For this, you can find a tutorial here: https://github.com/starknet-edu/deploy-cairo1-demo

Author: kahi.stark
Content: hello how do i derive a function selector in cairo, lets say i have a function "transfer" how do i get the function selector

Author: glihm
Content: You have to compute the starknet keccak function of your method's name to have the selector value. Only the name, this does not take any parenthesis or argument.

Author: glihm
Content: `0x0083afd3f4caedc6eebf44246fe54e38c95e3179a5ec9ea81740eca5b482d12e` is the selector for transfert.

Author: glihm
Content: (well, to be precised, you should use the starknet keccak, because the first 6 bits are not used. It's not exactly the keccak 256)

Author: glihm
Content:
You can use starkli to easily compute selector, or starknet.js.

https://github.com/xJonathanLEI/starkli#installation
Once installed: `starkli selector transfer`

https://www.starknetjs.com/docs/API/utils#starknetkeccak

Author: kahi.stark
Content: ahh alright thanks do i keccack hash the felt representation of the string "transfer"

Author: glihm
Content: Precisely you have to convert the string in bytes array, unset the 6 first bits of the first byte in the array, and pass this bytes array to starknet keccak function. üëç

Author: glihm
Content:
Does someone experienced this error 
```
Caused by:
    #17102: One of the arguments does not match the expected type of the libfunc or return statement.
```
when trying to implement `StorageAccess` on a custom struct?

Author: glihm
Content: Ok, the problem was from the `storage_read_syscall`. As the `read` from `StorageAccess` is expecting a `SyscallResult<MyType>`, there is something it's not accepting when doing `starknet::storage_read_syscall(....)?;`. So removing the `?` and using a match works fine as we don't automatically propagate the error.

Author: phil26
Content:
Hello,
In Cairo 2.0.0-rc6, the enum `Option` implements serialize/deserialize. So it can be used in Starknet contract as input or as response.
Unfortunately, the enum `Result` do not have this implementation, so can't be used in Starknet contract function signatures.
Is it planned to implement serialize/deserialize in `Result`?

Author: eni7912
Content: I think we could make a PR to the core library for this

Author: phil26
Content: I am currently  coding it directly in my test contract....

Author: eni7912
Content: `Result::Ok((value)) ` would become `[0,value]` and `Result::Err(value)` would become `[1,value]` like with options

Author: glihm
Content:
Since version 2.0.0, the way we declare contracts has changed: https://community.starknet.io/t/cairo-1-contract-syntax-is-evolving/94794/13
Here is the post.

You can also find in the cairo book the actualized syntax: https://cairo-book.github.io/ch99-01-02-writing-starknet-contracts.html.

Author: glihm
Content: There is not more `view`, the way you declare a function of the interface to be a `view` (not modifiying the state, which is the storage in this case), is by it's first parameter being a snapshot instead of a reference.

Author: wind.rider
Content:
ser,the team replied: "*In the underlying CASM - accesses to AP (allocation pointer) and FP (frame pointer) are with an offset of signed 16 bits - from a single location, without double deref - the possible addresses to access is limited.
This is not the size of the stack - but it is max size of the size that is actually viewable at a time*."

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
loop creates a recursive function around your logic, so `subject` ends up being moved into that function, and eventually can't be accessed when you want to return it at the end of the function (it's passed by ref). The workarounds then are:
1. Change subjects to `Span<ContractAddress>`, that way you don't lose ownership
2. Don't pass School by ref

Content: Hello! Arrays are not copiable. This is a rather expensive operation. If you do need a deep copy of your array, you can use `clone` instead: https://book.cairo-lang.org/ch03-01-what-is-ownership.html?highlight=Clone#copy-array-data-with-clone.

Author: eni7912
Content:
hey, 
1. There is a 256 field elements limitation to the maximal size of a complex storage value, meaning that to store arrays of more than 255 elements in storage, we would need to split it into segments of size n <= 255 and store these segments in multiple storage addresses. That's why the offset parameter in the internal read/write functions is a u8.

2. yes

Author: oriz1598
Content:
you cannot have `ref` arguments in the ABI - as you don't have access to edit the values provided to you from the outside:
but - you can have `mut` variable there:
either just have `mut data` instead of `ref data` (so you'd be able to append to it), or add a `let mut data = data` line.

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: Legacy map is a storage variable, like solidity's mapping. There is no way to iterate over all historical writes. If you want something like an array you have to store an index --> value mapping and iterate over the indices. Usually iterating over a mapping is not something you really want to do (in a sense it means going over all the state of my contract, which doesn't really make sense for a single tx and a large enough state).

Content: Does the call_contract_syscall return the (success,data) like we have in solidity

Author: akashneelesh
oriz1598
Content:
All our syscalls return `SyscallResult<T>` - which is `Result<T, Array<felt252>>` - where `T` is the valid result, and in case of a failure returns an array describing the error.
so after the `unwrap_syscall` it means we already got a valid result.

The output is indeed serialized in the result.

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
Most of the time you don't really need ecrecover. It becamse popular in the Ethereum ecosystem due to the coupling between the EOA addresses and public keys. We don't have EOAs, and public keys are stored in the account contract's storage.
This is an ECDSA verification over the STARK curve https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo/blob/6846d882c18337f6a5973970d38fd2ead6e8aa1a/corelib/src/ecdsa.cairo#L24
You can also verify Ethereum signatures (which is significantly more expensive and should only be done if it's critical to your usecase) https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo/blob/6846d882c18337f6a5973970d38fd2ead6e8aa1a/corelib/src/starknet/secp256_trait.cairo#L119, and the latter indeed relies on ecrecover https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo/blob/6846d882c18337f6a5973970d38fd2ead6e8aa1a/corelib/src/starknet/secp256_trait.cairo#L46

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content:
Storing arrays isn't supported
1. Today, storage structs can be of size <= 256 felts
2. To simulate arrays, you can use index=>value mapping and another length storage variable (you can't put mappings in structs)
3. In general, storing arrays doesn't really make sense (every storage write would potentially be very expensive and perform a lot of writes under the hood). One can think of a syntax for arrays storage that only supports writing to specific indices, but we don't have that ATM.

that is exactly the issue - you cannot read an enum that was never stored - unless you made sure its default makes sense:

#[derive(starknet::Store)]

    B: SomeOther
}
```

Author: akirillo
Content: hiya folks, I'm playing around with a generic waty to store large objects in contract storage (greater then 255 slots). I'm targeting version 2.0.1 of the compiler, so wouldn't be able to use `StorePacking`, but I can upgrade if it's the only way. This is pretty important for our application, but the `StorageAccess` interface seems to imply that its somewhat of an antipattern, e.g. because the `size_internal` method must return a `u8`. is there any precedent / any examples for this?

Author: wind.rider
Content: hi,ser,would you mind using this channel #üêûÔΩúscarb to check with the software mansion team? thank youüôèüèª

Author: oriz1598
Content: a single continuous object in the storage, can have a size of up to 256, if you want to pack large object, such as arrays, you should think of a way of packing them using multiple continuous objects.

Author: akirillo
Content: Yeah, my idea is basically to implement `read` on the `StorageAccess` trait to move to the next base address every 255 slots read, and vice versa for `write`. But then `size_internal` can‚Äôt really return a `u8`, and I‚Äôm not sure generally if this behavior is somehow unsupported - for example, in the trait method `read_internal_at_offset`, does the u8 offset make sense anymore? And where is this method invoked under the hood? These sorts of questions are hard for me to suss out

Author: oriz1598
Content: what is the "next base address"? not sure what are you planning - but the entire idea of the `Store` trait is exactly to block accesses larger than 256, while allowing easy implementation, if you want to implement a different access you'd need to use an entirely different trait.

Author: akirillo
Content:
Uhhh, `base_address_as_felt` + 256, lol

How can I use a different trait when all members of the `Storage` struct need to implement `StorageAccess`?

Is the most straightforward approach here to just store `StorageAddress`es in contract storage (since they implement `StorageAccess`)?

Author: akirillo
Content:
To that end, I‚Äôm a little unsure about the storage space layout. 

Let‚Äôs say I have two `StorageAddress`es, whose felt representations are 1 & 2. Are these still ‚Äú256 slots apart‚Äù? Or does a `StorageAddress` represent a single storage slot, meaning that if I have to write two 256-slot values, I should do it to `storage_address_1` and `storage_address_1 + 256`? I guess, then, is the point of the `StorageBaseAddress` type to represent 256-slot-aligned `StorageAddress`es?

The point of my questions being, that if I have to store large objects across multiple base addresses / 256-slot chunks, I need to know how to do the index arithmetic properly

Author: billlee
Content: how felt252 convert to uint256?

Author: oriz1598
Content:
you currently cannot write more than 256 cells continuously *by design* so that the chance of different vars colliding would not increase substantially.
so there is no such thing as "the next base address" - the entire point of the base address is to not allow it.

Author: oriz1598
Content: numerically - low would be `value % 2**128` high would be `value / 2**128`

Author: akirillo
Content:
This makes sense - but going back to the original problem, if I need to store an object larger than 256 slots in storage, what‚Äôs the best way to do it?

My next idea was to split it across multiple base addresses / 256-slot chunks, and store the addresses themselves in contract storage.

How should I pick those base addresses then? I don‚Äôt have access to any randomness within the runtime. So if not sequentially, then how?

Author: akashneelesh
Content:
I have a Span<felt252> and I wanna use keccak hashing on it , but then the keccak_u256s_be_inputs only takes in Span<u256>, So should i convert all the felt252 to u256 and then use the keccak fn.

Author: wind.rider
Content:
ser,it depends - keccak is defined on bits or bytes generally.
felt252s are numbers from 0..PRIME-1 - meaning - they do not represent a stream of bits.
So first you need to decide what is the relevant stream of bits, and only then we can decide how to actually put them into an input for our functionalities.

Author: glihm
Content:
Your intuition is correct, what happens is the following:

1. You send a message to the starknet core contract on L1.
2. This message is gathered by the starknet sequencer, which in turn sends a specific transaction type `L1Handler` automatically to the contract address you mentioned in your message.
3. The sequencer sets itself the from_address based on the message emitted by starknet core on L1.
4. You must always verify if this address is the one of your contract on L1 you are expected to send the messages.

Author: closer2282
Content:
Hi maybe you can check this post, hope it‚Äôll help
https://medium.com/starkware/cairo-roadmap-join-the-ride-23f31dcad172
> With the new Cairo compiler, we‚Äôre following the semantic versioning standard; that is, compiler versions consist of three digits, and a change in the most significant digit denotes breaking changes. With the next Cairo version, we have breaking changes in the smart contract syntax (described later in the post), so the correct thing to do is to bump the version to Cairo v2. To avoid cumbersome notation, we‚Äôll stop saying Cairo 1, and from now on, identify the language‚Äôs version with the (only) compiler version. The original language, which could still be used in the future in different contexts outside Starknet, will be referred to as ‚ÄúCairo 0‚Äù.''

Author: oriz1598
Content:
For me at least - the main idea - for methods, they generally have an obvious actuator - which is the `self` argument - so (hopefully) the name would be clear enough to state whether the function is ref/snapshot/value, and without it - method usage is very difficult. On general function all args are already enclosed in their own section (the `,` seperator) so the cost of being explicit is not too large, and the args themselves are not necessarily clear about if they are ref/snapshot/value.
Do note that this is a pretty similar approch to what rust do - &/&mut/value are explicit for everything but `self` params.

Author: gaetbout
wraitii
Content: I might be misunderstanding what `@` does in practice. My understanding is that it makes a variable essentially point to the 'past' memory cells, but 'right now' is included in that, so a `T` _is_ an `@T` . But it seems like within sierra it's more complicated than that

Author: wraitii
Content: I was under the impression that all const-read-only parameters to functions should be `@` by default (cc @eni ) but maybe that's wrong then ?

One with calldata (for the caller) and another one for the "client"  that'll handle the call, unless I'm missing smthng

Author: gaetbout
Content: Unless I can use a generic T and just give some struct

Author: oriz1598
Content: @T and T - are 2 different types - @T is the type of - T at some snapshot in time. so from T you can always get @T but it isn't @T by itself.

Author: wraitii
Content: I think that's where the definition kinda doesn't work for me, because a snapshot of `T right now` is `T`, logically speaking... But `@T` seems to shorthand for something more complicated under the surface, which means that the snapshot operation isn't actually 'free' step-wise

Author: oriz1598
Content:
The type for a reference to a snapshot in time, is not the same as the type itself.
These are just 2 different type.
Converting between these types is completely costless.

Author: wraitii
Content:
Just to be clear - I understand they're different types to the compiler. What I'm saying is to me they don't feel like they're different types, just different 'views' in to the same data maybe?
Anyways, I guess the core of my Q is that I don't see much value to being explicit about `@`. It just seems to add some syntactic noise in practice, and makes it more awkward to have function arguments that take `@`.

Author: gaetbout
Content: is there a way to know which operation is costless and which is not?

Author: eni7912
Content: copy and drop are costless I believe (so snap/desnap aswell), but I think the rest isn't. Basically if a libfunc doesn't generate casm code then it's free

Author: oriz1598
Content: it really isn't - as otherwise it isn't clear when you are performing a consuming operation, and when you are not - value actions are consuming, while on a snapshot they are not.

Author: wraitii
Content: Right, ok, so that's the meaningful difference

Author: wraitii
Content: But then I'd argue that any non-@, non-mut, non-ref function parameter is a developer mistake

Author: wraitii
Content: The only meaningful semantics are a ref-parameter, in which case it's explicit via `ref`, a read-only value, in which case it's best via `@`, or a mutable-consuming parameter, which doesn't have any explicit thingy at the callsite

Author: wraitii
Content: But I'd argue this makes the least common-case the most natural to write, which seems kinda backwards

Author: wraitii
Content: (in practice most `Copy` types avoid the issue, but in generic code it'll probably become annoying-ish)

Author: oriz1598
Content:
for a builder pattern for example - passing a value still makes complete sense.
In a function consuming an array of type T and returning a different array of type S it makes sense to get by value.
In any case you `want to consume` the value you should do it - and it is not uncommon.

Author: gaetbout
glihm
Content:
In that case, I would personally go with an interface for `B`, `C`, etc... to let the deserialization work being done by cairo directly and for better maintainability/testing.
But it's more work in `A`, to call the correct dispatcher.
Or you can use the `contract_call_syscall` directly, to always deal with serialized data in `A`, and only changing the address. This allows `A` to be a bit more generic, and `B`, `C`, ... to remain explicitely specific in their respective interfaces.

Author: glihm
Content: I've never tried yet, but can your interface be `ISomeInterface<TContractState, TData>` ? Then `some_fn` can be `some_fn(ref self: TContractState, data: Array<TData>)` and each Impl specifies it's data type and you remain generic in `A` sending the serialized array of felts.

I guess we have to discuss whether we want that functionality or not and see if it is a usecase we want on Starknet. Why do you need it btw? (btw, it's not available on Ethereum and opinions on this topic differ <https://ethereum-magicians.org/t/eip-2330-extsload-and-abi-for-lower-gas-cost-and-off-chain-apps/3733>)

Author: th0rgal.
Content:
I see. I think we can't predict all the future usecases of a smartcontract when deploying it but on the other hand, keeping all contracts upgradable to be able to add them in the future would not make a lot of sense on a blockchain. Allowing to read the storage of another contract would make the process of permissionlessly building on top much easier, and as upgradability would only be necessary for code actually writing to the storage, we would probably see more immutable contracts.

 Interesting thread btw. I didn't think about the Oracle usecase, but I am not convinced. We can already bypass that with storage proof, it's just making the process more complex, centralized and expensive.

Author: tekkac
Content:
Maybe if you can access "private" storage that says a certain storage proofs you are interested in has already been verified by someone else, then you don't need to pay for it anymore üòâ
You could also know if the function you're calling has a reentrancy guard.
But I agree those examples don't outweigh my feeling that such a syscall could be useful. And since it's not the first time you asked for it, maybe it's time to discuss it on the community forum?

Author: th0rgal.
Content:
I haven't tried to do it with Herodotus, what I mean is that if there is some kind of "private" storage in a contract, the design is already broken.  The only reason why it might not have been attacked yet is because it's a bit painful to do.

Because this private data can be read by the nodes, and can be proven to be valid on chain via a storage proof (hashing it with its neighbors until you get the root hash).

Author: grest_
Content:
I noticed that `u256_safe_divmod` now returns a `U128MulGuarantee` type. There is a comment that says "Additionally returns a `U128MulGuarantee` that is required for validating the calculation." Does this mean that we need to do something with the return value in order to verify the result is correct?

https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo/blob/ad8c151bc4d3a473061a09ddac1c2abe5d44fcf6/corelib/src/integer.cairo#L1237-L1241

Author: tekkac
Content: yes, it seems <https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo/blob/ad8c151bc4d3a473061a09ddac1c2abe5d44fcf6/corelib/src/integer.cairo#L66C36-L66C36>

Author: oriz1598
Content:
no - it does not mean you need to do anything manually. since Cairo has a linear type system, we know this guarantee object would be destructed.
This is just a way for us to easily make the underlying code more flexible.
Do note that it is quite unlikly you actualy want to call this function directly, but should call the wrapping function.

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826

Author: oriz1598
Content: Yes - there's a bug there - fixed at main (and at nesxt release)

Author: oriz1598
Content:
Calculations has costs as well - so not accessing storage does not necessarily mean all actions are free.
Generally - if you have an unknown number of steps in a test, you should add `#[available_gas(10000)]` to it (or any other number that makes sense)

Author: milan3774
Content:
yes, in the context of Starknet contracts, there has to be a struct called `Storage` and annotated with the `#[storage]` attribute

`LegacyMap` is just a mapping type (similar to dict in python or a hashmap in java), its just one of the types you can use for storage

Author: gaetbout
Content:
when should we put a fn within a 
```rust
    #[generate_trait]
    impl Private of PrivateTrait {}
```
and when should we just put it at the contract level so it is accessible without using self.X()
?

Author: milan3774
Content:
heh, we've been having this same discussion this week, trying to come with a convention

what we've decided on is that stateful (needing `self: @ContractState` or its `ref`) functions we put inside this Private trait and stateless helper functions we put on the top level

note that you can still access stateless helper functions that are inside the generated trait when prefixing them with the impl name, e.g. `Private::foo()`

Author: oriz1598
Content:
In the final current CASM stage, everything is felt252.
but in Cairo (which directly compiles to Sierra) it does not, if some sort of vectoric operations are implemented, this would be possible. otherwise - each unit is by itself.
for storage - you can pack your structs in whatever method youd like - so having a struct of:
```
struct MyStruct { a: u64, b: u64, c: u64 }
```
you can pack these into a single storage cell (by simple arithmetic operations)

Author: eni7912
Content: any specific reason why `TryInto` is `T -> Option<S>` and not `<T -> Err<S, E>>` ?

Author: oriz1598
Content:
no it does not - you generally should not go to the final CASM to decide which type you should use. Sierra hides the underlying structure - that can basically change in the future for optimization.
I would recommend using the amount of data required for your usecase, be it u8 or u128.

Author: oriz1598
Content:
mostly since the failure itself is already rather specific - conversion failed - specific reason can be added by the caller.
Otherwise all TryInto providers would have needed to provide a special error type as well.

Author: satyambnsal
Content:
Hi, 
I'm bit confused about the mutable reference definition and its internal working. 
so on  Cairo book, it says, 

does this mean that when we call a function that takes mutable reference as a argument for a variable x, it is passing ownership of that variable inside a function context and implicitly returning it at the end ?

Author: satyambnsal
Content: If this is the case, IMO this behaviour is very different from rust. because in rust, mutable references do not take ownership of the variable. Ownership is a property of values, and references are just pointers to values. A mutable reference allows you to modify the value that it points to, but it does not own the value itself.

Author: raphael_doukhan
Content:
What‚Äôs the reason why LegacyMap can only be used in storage?

I want to simulate the mutability of an array using a hash table. Felt252Dict uses a list of entries. This means that for read/write interactions, the average time complexity is O(n). This is why I would prefer to use hash tables instead

Author: oriz1598
Content:
`update_with` is generally the correct one.

more info:
`update` is the base function of a hashstate to update using a felt252.
`update_state` is the base function of a hashable object - how to add itself onto a state, assuming it has `update`.
`update_with` mixes the two actions onto the hash-state directly, working for all types.

Author: veoquynhs
Content:
Hi! I'm wondering how to read and write from a nested mapping store in storage?
`is_claimed: LegacyMap<ContractAddress, (u32, bool)>,` 
I tried `self.is_claimed.read(user).read(claimTurn);` , which `user` is `ContractAddress`, and `claimTurn` is `u32`, but it fails

Author: milan3774
Content: here, `is_claimed` is not a nested mapping, the stored value is a 2-tuple, so you can do `let (claim_turn, _) = self.is_claimed.read(user);`

Author: veoquynhs
Content: Oh, I see, so how can I get the `bool` value?

Author: milan3774
Content:
in a similar manner - `let (claim_turn, the_bool) = self....`

see the Cairo book to learn about tuples and destructuring https://book.cairo-lang.org/ch02-02-data-types.html#the-tuple-type

Author: veoquynhs
Content: I got it, thank you!

Author: veoquynhs
Content: In my case, I want to store the tuple somewhat like a nested mapping, which mapped from the `user`, for example `claim_turn = 1 => the_bool `  is true, `claim_turn = 2 => the_bool` is false, `claim_turn = 3 => ...` Do we have any way to do this?

Author: milan3774
Content: yes, you can use a tuple in the "key" of a `LegacyMap`, so `is_claimed: LegacyMap<(ContractAddress, u32), bool>` and then use `.read((user, claim_turn))` to get the boolean

Author: tothemoon8836
Content: thx ,I resolve this

Author: glihm
Content: If you don't use `#[starknet::contract]` then it will be compiled as a regular cairo module. Keep in mind that Cairo is a programming language that can live without Starknet (event if it's designed for starknet in a sense). So you wouldn't be able to have the files you want to declare and deploy on chain without this attribute. As @eni also said, if you don't use this attribute, it's NOT a cairo contract.

Author: glihm
Content:
There is not "side effects" in the sense that keys are here for a specific purpose. How are you testing? That's the test?
The important effect (and not side hehe) of `#[keys]` is that when the event if emitted, you have two fields: `keys` and `data` and depending on the attribute `#[keys]` your value will be in one arra of the other.
